Actually the thinking started about 200 BC. Ancient Greek mathematician Philolaos proved that the sum of the first $n$ numbers is approximately equal to the sum of the first $n$ odd positive integers (i.e. the number of stars shown in the following stereophotograph). What is this sum? Suppose you is 
$$1+2+3+\cdots+n.$$
What you want to find is
$$1+3+5+\cdots+(2n-1).$$
But
$$1+2+3+\cdots +n=\frac{n(n-1)}{2}.$$
And
$$1+3+5+\cdots+(2n-1)=1+2+3+4+\cdots+(2n-1)-(2+4+6+\cdots+2(n-1)).$$
So we have
$$1+3+5+\cdots+(2n-1)=1+2+3+4+\cdots+(2n-1)-(2+4+6+\cdots+2(n-1))$$
$$=1+2+3+4+\ldots+(2n-1)-2(1+2+3+\cdots+(n-1))=(1+2+3+\cdots+2n-1)-2(1+2+3+\cdots+(n-1))$$
$$=\frac{2n(2n-1)}{2}-\frac{2(n-1)(n-2)}{2}=0.5(n+2n-4)=1.5n-2.$$
